content.description: Stand start using the good right-hand rail and left-hand sloper. Hand-heel match on the rail to get off the ground, and work your way up the arete using compression beta and technical footwork to a delicate topout.Overall good landing except for the granite wall that comes very close to the climber near the top out. The polished granite can make the top out very sketchy until the moves are worked out. A good spotter with a spot pad is advised.A hard extension to this problem is possible by going lower on the dihedral.
content.location: This problem encompasses the prominent dihedral in the cave perma-shaded by the Futurama Entrance Slab boulder.

content.description: Sit start down and right at a flat rail and climb up and left using your choice of holds.
content.location: Walk through the triangular tunnel formed by the two boulders. Sit start on rails on at the back of the left boulder.

content.description: Stand onto the base of the right-leaning seam, reach left to a small side pull and stand onto the ramp. With the side pull as the last handhold, continue to the top using feet only.
content.location: On the larger boulder to hiker's right before passing through the constriction.

content.description: Sit start at a waist height rail. Climb the arete up and left.
content.location: On the larger boulder to hiker's right before passing through the constriction.

content.description: Climb the right-trending seam. If it's too easy for your liking, try a hands-free ascent.
content.location: On the larger boulder to hiker's right before passing through the constriction.

content.description: Sit start and climb the arete on slightly grainy edges. Roll left onto the face at head height.
content.location: On the larger boulder to hiker's right before passing through the constriction.

content.description: Climb the slab to the left of the right-trending seam.
content.location: On the larger boulder to hiker's right before passing through the constriction.

content.description: To the left of the cave, climb small dishes and edges using feet only.
Cruxy moves through a narrow pinch in the thin flake lead to a non-trivial mantle topout.
content.location: Start sitting beneath the roof, climb left to a juggy slot, then make a big move straight up to a narrow pinch and climb to the sloping arete via a thin flake.

content.description: Climb the featured slab on the right side of the boulder.
content.location: On the larger boulder to hiker's right before passing through the constriction.

content.description: Sit start on the right arete of the right boulder with a flat hold. Stand up on crimps and jugs.
content.location: This is the right of the two boulders found immediately upstream of the entrance wall.

content.description: Sit start on the left with a slopey softball sized hueco. Move straight up on plates and crimps. A slightly harder variation starts right hand in the hueco, moving left to a flat edge before making a move to the bucket.
content.location: The left side of the face of the right boulder that forms the tunnel immediately upstream from the entrance wall.

content.description: Mantle onto the small, curved dihedral and balance to the top.
content.location: In the center of the small vertical face at the top of the rocks at the back of the cave.

content.description: Climb the slab right of Seam but without using the good slab features to your right. A bit contrived.
content.location: On the larger boulder to hiker's right before passing through the constriction.

content.description: Starting at the back of the cave, hand jam and stem to the front and pull over on top of the boulders.

These are the collection of boulders past the Front Boulder Wall but before the constriction that leads to Snake Eyes Wall and the rest of the canyon. With problems ranging from VB-V8ish (the "-ish" is because of an unfinished project in the cave that likely goes at around V8), this is probably the best place in the canyon for a proper warm-up.
